frameDefinitions: In this frame an Experiencer experiences an Emotion or is in an Emotional_state.
A Potential_hindrance or an Agent (via their actions) keeps an Event from taking place, or despite the possibility of prevent the Event, do not do so.
This frame contains nouns that refer to sensations in different modalities.
An Experiencer must cope with some Condition for a prolonged period, usually against his or her will.
An Owner has (or lacks) a Possession. '' 'The river's part of my  manor, but of course it also belongs to the River Police.'
A Cognizer holds a particular Opinion, which may be portrayed as being about a particular Topic.
frameExamples: Rain <t>prevented</t> the ball game from taking place.
The huge sand dunes, perpetually changing, make for a surreal <t>sight</t>.
The river's part of my  manor, but of course it also <t>belongs</t> to the River Police.
John <t>thinks</t> that it looks better back .
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences the <fen>Emotion</fen> or is in the <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
The <fen>Emotion</fen> is the feeling that the <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences.
The <fen>Emotional_state</fen> is the state the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in.
The <fen>Evaluation</fen> is a negative or positive assessment of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> regarding his or her <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
The <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> is the force which keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from happening, or does not.
The <fen>Event</fen> is prevented from occurring by the <fen>Preventing_cause</fen> or the <fen>Agent</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the sentient being which keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from happening.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> or <fen>Agent</fen> keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from taking place.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> or <fen>Agent</fen> keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from taking place.
This role is only expressed with certain nouns in this frame, and then only with the help of a support verb, such as <ment>have</ment>:

This is the entity or phenomenon which gives rise to the sensation. In cases of veridical sensation, this role is not typically distinguished from <fen>Percept</fen>. Most of the phrases that express this role can be paraphrased as <ment>from</ment>-phrases, e.g.

The role <fen>Percept</fen> is used for phrases that express the characteristic property of a sensation. Typically this characteristic property is described with reference to the entity or phenomenon that produces the sensation---that  is why this role can be difficult to distinguish from Source. It is possible for Source and Percept to be expressed separately, however:

This role is assigned to phrases expressing the body part in which a sensation is located. Since touch is the least localized of sense modalities, words relating to haptic sensations are the ones most likely to occur with this FE:
This role is the perceptual background against which the Phenomenon is experienced by the Perceiver.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the sensation is perceived.
A person who experiences the effects of some situation or <fen>Condition</fen> for a long period of time.
This role describes the situation that the <fen>Experiencer</fen> must cope with over a long period of time.
A general description of the temporal location of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> while coping with the <fen>Condition</fen>.
Where the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is located when he or she faces the <fen>Condition</fen>.
The entity that owns a posession.

The thing which is owned by the Owner.
Ex.:  I <t>have</t> <fex name='Possession'>twenty bucks</fex>.
(This does not include bodyparts or medical conditions, but does include intellectual property, etc.)
This role indicates the <fen>Time</fen> interval during which the <fen>Owner</fen> has a possession.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person whose <fen>Opinion</fen> is in question.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen>'s way of thinking, which is not necessarily generally accepted, and which is generally dependent on the <fen>Cognizer</fen>'s point of view.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> has the <fen>Opinion</fen>.
listRoleExamples: After two pints, <fex>he</fex> felt a bit better and Ted arrived.
Patients experience <fex>high anxiety levels</fex> at time of admission to hospital.
Her heart was galloping so fast that she felt <fex>quite giddy with happiness</fex>.
Max was feeling <fex>worse than he'd ever felt in his life</fex>.
<fex>I</fex> have a tingling sensation in my hands.
The smell <fex>of the garlic</fex> made me hungry.
This herb gives off a smell <fex>of garlic</fex>.
I have a tingling feeling <fex>in my hands</fex>.
<fex>My</fex> take is that Johnson will not actually make it to the last round .

My take is <fex>that it is a version of the Macbeth story - what happens when people
become violent but cannot quite handle it</fex>.
